<div id="review_2419849425" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2419849425" />
    <a title="Ksenia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11227522-ksenia"><img alt="Ksenia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1427672662p2/11227522.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2419849425?book_show_action=true">Jun 10, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ksenia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ksenia" href="/user/show/11227522-ksenia">Ksenia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780062109569" href="/book/show/11224012-nom-de-plume">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11227522-ksenia?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11227522-ksenia?shelf=biographies">biographies</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2419849425" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6802940217742947331">A biography of 18 nineteenth and twentieth century authors who used pseudonyms. This includes the likes of the Brontë sisters, Romain Gary, Mark Twain, George Orwell, and others. Some used the anonymity to publish shocking material, some created personas that would give the author credibility over a subject matter, while some housed multiple personalities. <br/><br/>Some of the chapters are engaging and describe unusual lives and circumstances — the last chapter on Pauline Réage especially was fascinating</span>
  <span id="freeText6802940217742947331" style="display:none">A biography of 18 nineteenth and twentieth century authors who used pseudonyms. This includes the likes of the Brontë sisters, Romain Gary, Mark Twain, George Orwell, and others. Some used the anonymity to publish shocking material, some created personas that would give the author credibility over a subject matter, while some housed multiple personalities. <br /><br />Some of the chapters are engaging and describe unusual lives and circumstances — the last chapter on Pauline Réage especially was fascinating because of the themes it wrestled with and the modern consequences of her work — while others can be quite hard to get through. There is also a feeling of disconnection between the different chapters. The order of chapters is chronological based on the years when the authors were alive, but since the book is an exploration of pseudonyms it would have been great to dedicate some space to connecting the stories together. Some authors could not withstand the pressures of fame once their pseudonyms were stripped from them, some had insecurities and vulnerabilities that haunted them since childhood, while others assumed pseudonyms to free themselves from societal constraints. It would have been interesting to bridge those themes across chapters and it may have made some of the dryer chapters more interesting. <br /><br />The most engaging chapters, which I would highly recommend, were the following: Brontë sisters, Fernando Pessoa, Romain Gary, Georges Simenon, and Pauline Réage.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6802940217742947331" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

