<div id="review_172901462" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/172901462" />
    <a title="Evan Kingston" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5001200-evan-kingston"><img alt="Evan Kingston" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442944856p2/5001200.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/172901462?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Evan Kingston" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Evan Kingston" href="/user/show/5001200-evan-kingston">Evan Kingston</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer172901462" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13900294604544761163">I won this on First Reads--and really enjoyed my time with it.<br/><br/>The book explores the motives, circumstances, and effects of pen-names throughout literary history by studying the biographies of a dozen authors who wrote under aliases. Ciuraru has many interesting things to say about literature in general and nom de plumes in particular and a real eye for the most tantalizing tidbits of a biography. Much of the juiciest details in the book are what informs the choice to use a pen-name, so it is all</span>
  <span id="freeText13900294604544761163" style="display:none">I won this on First Reads--and really enjoyed my time with it.<br /><br />The book explores the motives, circumstances, and effects of pen-names throughout literary history by studying the biographies of a dozen authors who wrote under aliases. Ciuraru has many interesting things to say about literature in general and nom de plumes in particular and a real eye for the most tantalizing tidbits of a biography. Much of the juiciest details in the book are what informs the choice to use a pen-name, so it is all guilt-free gossip in pursuit of literary knowledge. It was great learning new facts about authors I love and finding out about fascinating authors I have yet to read.<br /><br />If I had one complaint, it was that in trying to tightrope walk between academic exploration and popular biography, the book occasionally lost it's momentum. In the introduction, Ciuraru lays out some interesting conclusions about the use of pen-names in the past and their renewed importance in our privacy-starved internet-age--but then settles for a few small editorial comments throughout the rest of the chapters, letting her views take a backseat to biography. I would have preferred the book was a little more academically rigorous and focused more on synthesizing rather than just reporting her research. While I realize I may be I the minority because this sort of biography will certainly help it find a wider audience, there are parts in Ciuraru's otherwise deft handling of biographical details where she seems to want to reorganize them into an argument; at least once a chapter, she seems to jump or stray confusingly out of chronology to pile up details and make a point about nom de plumes. But before she goes all the way into theory, she hurries back to the story she left off at and follows the author's life to it's conclusion (even through details that have little bearing on the book's actual subject).<br /><br /> I guess the book finds an admirable balance, though, and these sections were really just blips in a very fun and illuminating read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13900294604544761163" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

