<span id="freeTextContainer16018236064859652298">I love reading about the life of these authors - particularly why or how they chose their pseudonym. I am also quotes from other classic authors about the person addressed.<br/><br/>Grew tired of this book eventually. When it came to the authors I had never heard of (nor want to read now that I know about their personal lives). <br/><br/><br/>Four stars to the chapters about: Acton, Currer &amp; Ellis Bell; Aurore Dupin; Marian Evans; Charles Dodgson; and Samuel Clemens.<br/><br/>One star to the chapters about: Fernando Pessoa; Emile</span>
  <span id="freeText16018236064859652298" style="display:none">I love reading about the life of these authors - particularly why or how they chose their pseudonym. I am also quotes from other classic authors about the person addressed.<br /><br />Grew tired of this book eventually. When it came to the authors I had never heard of (nor want to read now that I know about their personal lives). <br /><br /><br />Four stars to the chapters about: Acton, Currer &amp; Ellis Bell; Aurore Dupin; Marian Evans; Charles Dodgson; and Samuel Clemens.<br /><br />One star to the chapters about: Fernando Pessoa; Emile Ajar; Christian Brulls; and Claire Morgan.<br /><br />Didn't finish the chapter about Claire Morgan or even attempt Dominique Aury - why bother?<br /><br />Overall - I would recommend specific chapters in this book to anyone who is teaching these authors, has read these authors, or is attempting their own Nom De Plume in their writing process.<br />-------------------------------------------<br />"She felt that as a writer, she had nothing important to say - of at least nothing that would be heard. She was expected to be a devoted wife a faithful, hard working CIA operative; with whatever energy was left, she could attempt to write.</span>
